<div id="review_363690453" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/363690453" />
    <a title="Marije" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5988085-marije"><img alt="Marije" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1467123413p2/5988085.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/363690453?book_show_action=true">Jul 08, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marije" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marije" href="/user/show/5988085-marije">Marije</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140032062" href="/book/show/3206428-the-devils-of-loudun">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer363690453&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer363690453" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1308999184625203934">In this interpretation of historic events, Huxley tries to explain how it was possible that an obviously innocent man, the priest Urbain Grandier, was accused of sorcery and burned at the stake in seventeen-century Loudun, France.<br/>Most of it is politics, as were witchhunts in general. But here it was not only small-town grievances that led one neighbour to accuse another of witchcraft; Richelieu&apos;s influences at the French court, contra-reformation and personal vendetta&apos;s make the prosecution, con</span>
  <span id="freeText1308999184625203934" style="display:none">In this interpretation of historic events, Huxley tries to explain how it was possible that an obviously innocent man, the priest Urbain Grandier, was accused of sorcery and burned at the stake in seventeen-century Loudun, France.<br />Most of it is politics, as were witchhunts in general. But here it was not only small-town grievances that led one neighbour to accuse another of witchcraft; Richelieu's influences at the French court, contra-reformation and personal vendetta's make the prosecution, condemnation and burning of a priest seem almost inevitable. After all, the accused slept around, laughed in powerful people's faces, turned down the wrong person and was loved by his parish. He was, therefore, a danger to those in power, not because he disputed them or waged war against them, but because he made them look stupid.<br /><br />This historical reconstruction is a strong plot on its own, but Huxley doesn't stop there. He adds a provocative and fascinating layer to the story when he dives into the religious and scientific frames of thought that were available to the people of western Europe in the 17th century.<br />Not only is Huxley knowable and thoughtful in his descriptions of various dogma's then and now (or Huxley's now, 1954), he also succeeds in explaining why belief in devils and possession was so natural to people, and not only to the illiterate and poor masses, but to the rich, powerful and smart as well. <br />The priest had friends who were sure he was being set up, and there certainly were scpetics regarding witchcraft and possessions. But these were a minority and they had to be carefull not to be branded as heretics themselves (indeed, dome of them were found guilty as well). The men who had Grandier's faith in their hands were convinced of his guilt, of the reality of demons, of the neccesity of exorcism. The fact that these very exorcisms created the symptoms of the possessed never occured to them. The hysteria, the devils, the convulsions, the pain, the punishment, the blasphemy, the vulgarities, the emotions; all were consciously and subcosciously created for the greater good. The most succesful lies are believed by the ones who tell them. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1308999184625203934" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

