<div id="review_2754934437" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2754934437" />
    <a title="Brett" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/436346-brett"><img alt="Brett" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1195094919p2/436346.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2754934437?book_show_action=true">Apr 17, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brett" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brett" href="/user/show/436346-brett">Brett</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/436346-brett?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/436346-brett?shelf=religion">religion</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/436346-brett?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2754934437" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6844079123121980925">What is this book, exactly?<br/><br/>It exists in some netherworld between fiction and non-fiction. It&apos;s history and philosophy and theology. It&apos;s a book about mass delusion, politics, torture, and redemption.<br/><br/>It&apos;s interesting though it reads sometimes as unfocused. When I started it, I was under the impression that I was picking up a work of fiction (though based on historical happenings) in the same vein as Huxley&apos;s other fiction. And sometimes the way that Huxley talks about the inner thoughts of the hi</span>
  <span id="freeText6844079123121980925" style="display:none">What is this book, exactly?<br /><br />It exists in some netherworld between fiction and non-fiction. It's history and philosophy and theology. It's a book about mass delusion, politics, torture, and redemption.<br /><br />It's interesting though it reads sometimes as unfocused. When I started it, I was under the impression that I was picking up a work of fiction (though based on historical happenings) in the same vein as Huxley's other fiction. And sometimes the way that Huxley talks about the inner thoughts of the historical personages does indeed seem novelistic. But as the book wears on, it becomes more and more dedicated to non-fiction style, even including footnotes and citations to other works. <br /><br />For the first half of the book, I was pretty convinced that I didn't care for it at all. But the second half is much stronger and compelling. It's a story of trumped up witchcraft allegations in a French monastery and the way those allegations were used to punish a priest who had made powerful enemies because of his philandering with the daughter of a local towns-person. <br /><br />Once we reach the section of the book that deals directly with these allegations, the displays of possession put on by the nuns, and the resulting trial and gruesome death of the priest, the book is riveting. I wish we could cut out large sections of Huxley's navel-gazing theology and his overly-credulous talk about ESP and other extrasensory phenomena. (If you've read much of Huxley's later period non-fiction, you'll know that he was a big believer in a lot of mumbo jumbo.)<br /><br />I didn't know anything about this historical incident prior to picking up this book. Seems ripe for a more accessible treatment, since the story is out of this world. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6844079123121980925" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

