<div id="review_2764716799" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2764716799" />
    <a title="Jason" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27714141-jason"><img alt="Jason" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2764716799?book_show_action=true">Jun 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jason" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jason" href="/user/show/27714141-jason">Jason</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27714141-jason?shelf=religion">religion</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27714141-jason?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27714141-jason?shelf=christian-lit">christian-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27714141-jason?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2764716799" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10144864860483691473">&quot;Moby Dick&quot; contains an infamous chapter titled Cetology in which Herman Melville pauses his plot so he can share whale facts. While marine biology can be fascinating, Melville&apos;s digression stops his story cold.<br/><br/>Aldous Huxley makes the same mistake repeatedly in &quot;The Devils of Loudun.&quot;<br/><br/>&quot;Loudon&quot; ostensibly tells the true story of Urbain Grandier and Jeanne des Anges. Grandier was a charismatic, arrogant and well-connected priest. He also lacked discretion with his female parishioners -- impregnatin</span>
  <span id="freeText10144864860483691473" style="display:none">"Moby Dick" contains an infamous chapter titled Cetology in which Herman Melville pauses his plot so he can share whale facts. While marine biology can be fascinating, Melville's digression stops his story cold.<br /><br />Aldous Huxley makes the same mistake repeatedly in "The Devils of Loudun."<br /><br />"Loudon" ostensibly tells the true story of Urbain Grandier and Jeanne des Anges. Grandier was a charismatic, arrogant and well-connected priest. He also lacked discretion with his female parishioners -- impregnating one, secretly marrying another, and otherwise indulging his licentiousness.<br /><br />This might not have mattered. A priest with a mistress or two didn't merit a scandal in 17th century France. However, Grandier had a knack for accruing enemies, including the aforementioned Anges and Cardinal Richelieu.<br /><br />Anges was the young prioress of a nearby Ursuline nunnery. She fixated on the handsome priest, but he offended her when he refused her invitation to become the convent's spiritual director. Soon she began seeing lecherous visions of Grandier. Some of her young nuns followed suit. Soon thereafter, Anges and some of Grandier's powerful enemies claimed the priest was a witch.<br /><br />Grandier's crimes, trial (which had nothing to do with his crimes,) and execution make for a powerful story. But Huxley can't resist his digressions. He interrupts his narrative so he can tell you about social mores in the 17th century, the forms of transcendence, a brief history of the apothecary trade, and other distractions.<br /><br />Huxley's a polymath and has researched his many topics well. But if I wanted to read Huxley's take on mysticism, I'd have re-read "The Perennial Philosophy."</span>
  <a data-text-id="10144864860483691473" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


