    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1721334120" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1721334120" />
    <a title="Owain" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13681589-owain"><img alt="Owain" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563024930p2/13681589.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1721334120?book_show_action=true">Oct 02, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Owain" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Owain" href="/user/show/13681589-owain">Owain</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140032062" href="/book/show/3206428-the-devils-of-loudun">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1721334120" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12463545610645356128">This book pushes the boundaries of how much tedium I can endure in fiction. It&apos;s drier than the Mojave Desert. Despite the subject matter being interesting Huxley manages to suck all the excitement out of it like the Hungry Caterpillar munching its way rapidly through a pile of cotton wool. I don&apos;t understand how a scene where a guy is wrongly accused of witchcraft and burned alive at the stake can be made so undramatic and dull.<br/><br/>My constructive criticism to Huxley (if he wasn&apos;t dead) would be to</span>
  <span id="freeText12463545610645356128" style="display:none">This book pushes the boundaries of how much tedium I can endure in fiction. It's drier than the Mojave Desert. Despite the subject matter being interesting Huxley manages to suck all the excitement out of it like the Hungry Caterpillar munching its way rapidly through a pile of cotton wool. I don't understand how a scene where a guy is wrongly accused of witchcraft and burned alive at the stake can be made so undramatic and dull.<br /><br />My constructive criticism to Huxley (if he wasn't dead) would be to focus on the character of Urbain Grandier. This novel lacks a protagonist and reads like a history textbook and Grandier would be the natural choice. Then I would end the novel at, or very briefly after Grandier's death. I wouldn't do what Huxley did and write several chapters of waffle afterwards. The author's philosophical pondering are all well and good. They are actually quite interesting. But the novel doesn't need it. The novel needs a character to relate to.<br /><br />If I was going to muse on the origins of psychology and treatment for the mentally ill and how it arose from belief in possessions and the process of exorcism I'd put that shit into an essay. Or at least if you do put it in a novel: make it interesting. Huxley is good at inventing interesting concepts but they are interesting in spite of, not because of his writing. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12463545610645356128" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

