        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer415050111" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1498858646835909432">A fascinating account of a reported case of devil possession in Loudun France in the early 17th Century that resulted in the execution of a Priest who was most certainly not guilty. Cardinal Richelieu plays a prominent role in the course of events.<br/><br/>Be forewarned that this is not a straightforward retelling. Huxley is an excellent expository writer (at times a little pedantic) and the book provides a wealth of information on French society of the early 17th Century. But Huxley was also interested </span>
  <span id="freeText1498858646835909432" style="display:none">A fascinating account of a reported case of devil possession in Loudun France in the early 17th Century that resulted in the execution of a Priest who was most certainly not guilty. Cardinal Richelieu plays a prominent role in the course of events.<br /><br />Be forewarned that this is not a straightforward retelling. Huxley is an excellent expository writer (at times a little pedantic) and the book provides a wealth of information on French society of the early 17th Century. But Huxley was also interested in "cosmic" issues, and there are long digressions (including Chapter 3 entire) that provides Huxley's views on the soul, etc. Without this, I would have given the book 5 stars, but I'm not saying his digressions are without merit. They just weaken the strength of his narrative in my opinion.<br /><br />Also be warned that there are stretches in untranslated French (including the "dirty parts").</span>
  <a data-text-id="1498858646835909432" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


